WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:01.235 --> 00:00:02.269
[Michael]
<i>Previously on</i> Will Trent <i>...</i>

2
00:00:02.402 --> 00:00:03.972
[Amanda]
<i>Let's talk about Paul Campano.</i>

3
00:00:04.104 --> 00:00:05.239
Get off me. Trashcan.

4
00:00:05.372 --> 00:00:06.674
[Abigail] <i>You know each other?</i>

5
00:00:06.808 --> 00:00:08.610
Paul and I grew up together
in the children's home.

6
00:00:08.743 --> 00:00:10.879
I can't believe
you guys are still hooking up.

7
00:00:11.011 --> 00:00:13.213
You know there's a whole world
out there full of people.
right?

8
00:00:13.347 --> 00:00:15.984
-You have nightmares? Me too.
-Four nights out of seven.

9
00:00:16.116 --> 00:00:17.652
I was gonna kill you.

10
00:00:17.785 --> 00:00:20.153
There is a monster in there
after all.

11
00:00:20.287 --> 00:00:22.690
You brought calamity
upon our family.

12
00:00:22.824 --> 00:00:24.324
-[screams]
-[gunshot]

13
00:00:24.826 --> 00:00:27.529
[grunts] See you soon.

14
00:00:28.997 --> 00:00:29.964
[person] No! [sobs]

15
00:00:30.097 --> 00:00:32.132
[♪ sinister music playing]

16
00:00:33.166 --> 00:00:34.869
[whimpers. screams]

17
00:00:37.705 --> 00:00:39.874
Why are you doing this?
[sobbing]

18
00:00:43.210 --> 00:00:44.579
[nail gun fires]

19
00:00:45.178 --> 00:00:46.179
[knife clatters]

20
00:00:50.852 --> 00:00:51.886
[screams]

21
00:00:53.487 --> 00:00:54.622
[nail gun fires]

22
00:00:56.323 --> 00:00:57.959
Please. Don't.

23
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:05.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

24
00:01:06.568 --> 00:01:08.101
[water sloshing]

25
00:01:08.703 --> 00:01:10.004
-[groaning]
-Oopsie.

26
00:01:11.271 --> 00:01:14.042
-Sorry about that.
-[sighs]

27
00:01:14.174 --> 00:01:16.276
-[siren wailing]
-[camera clicking]

28
00:01:16.410 --> 00:01:18.613
[♪ tense music playing]

29
00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:30.190
The victim. Joelle Hornbaker.
could have escaped.
She stopped.

30
00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:32.994
Why?

31
00:01:34.394 --> 00:01:36.430
Death was waiting
in the opposite direction.

32
00:01:45.573 --> 00:01:48.408
The angle of these nails
suggests the killer
was much taller.

33
00:01:48.943 --> 00:01:50.243
assumed to be male.

34
00:01:50.377 --> 00:01:51.746
Given the unique choice
of weaponry.

35
00:01:51.879 --> 00:01:53.648
he wanted Mrs. Hornbaker
to suffer.

36
00:01:53.781 --> 00:01:55.617
No signs of forced entry
anywhere.

37
00:01:55.750 --> 00:01:58.118
and it doesn't look like
anything was stolen
in the house.

38
00:01:59.821 --> 00:02:01.121
Anyone get a hold
of her husband?

39
00:02:01.254 --> 00:02:03.290
Eli Hornbaker was notified
an hour ago.

40
00:02:03.423 --> 00:02:05.593
He's on his way back from
a business trip in Memphis.

41
00:02:07.227 --> 00:02:09.229
The killer knew she was alone.

42
00:02:09.797 --> 00:02:12.165
Mrs. Hornbaker was the target
of this home invasion.

43
00:02:12.900 --> 00:02:13.935
How are we doing there?

44
00:02:14.569 --> 00:02:16.004
I'm not finding anything.

45
00:02:17.071 --> 00:02:20.008
No smudges.
no fabric impressions. nothing?

46
00:02:20.140 --> 00:02:21.109
Not a one.

47
00:02:21.241 --> 00:02:22.275
Well. keep looking.

48
00:02:23.745 --> 00:02:25.113
The killer
wiped down the scene.

49
00:02:25.245 --> 00:02:26.848
Nothing we haven't seen before.

50
00:02:26.981 --> 00:02:29.316
But how often
do they clean for prints
and leave us the murder weapon

51
00:02:29.449 --> 00:02:30.484
for us to find?

52
00:02:31.052 --> 00:02:32.352
Never.

53
00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:41.829
[Will] She reached
for this drawer...

54
00:02:43.296 --> 00:02:46.501
to get a knife
to defend herself.
a chef's knife.

55
00:02:47.802 --> 00:02:48.770
So where is it?

56
00:02:48.903 --> 00:02:49.971
You collect a knife?

57
00:02:51.005 --> 00:02:52.272
Nope.

58
00:02:52.406 --> 00:02:53.741
[Faith] Maybe the killer
took it with him.

59
00:02:54.441 --> 00:02:57.377
She could have defended herself
and gotten a piece of him.

60
00:02:58.513 --> 00:03:01.849
No. I didn't let her
get that close.

61
00:03:02.650 --> 00:03:03.818
You?

62
00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:07.889
-What?
-[Paul] Excuse me.
No. I... Let me through.

63
00:03:08.022 --> 00:03:10.490
I live on this street.
I have some information.

64
00:03:10.625 --> 00:03:12.026
-What the hell is this?
-I didn't come to talk

65
00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:13.528
to a schmo in a uniform.

66
00:03:13.661 --> 00:03:15.863
Let me talk to the main guy.
whoever's in charge. Not you.

67
00:03:15.997 --> 00:03:17.031
Paul?

68
00:03:17.165 --> 00:03:19.567
Will. Thank God.
See? This is what I meant.

69
00:03:19.701 --> 00:03:21.035
This is who I talk to.

70
00:03:21.169 --> 00:03:22.436
What the hell
are you doing here?

71
00:03:22.570 --> 00:03:24.371
I live down the street.
I moved a couple years ago.

72
00:03:24.505 --> 00:03:27.041
Okay. Remember my partner.
Special Agent Faith Mitchell?

73
00:03:27.508 --> 00:03:30.178
Yeah. hi.
Listen. I know who did it.

74
00:03:32.345 --> 00:03:33.548
[Will sighs]

75
00:03:35.616 --> 00:03:37.185
Paul. this looks like
a toddler drew it.

76
00:03:37.350 --> 00:03:40.387
What?
It has all the key descriptors.

77
00:03:40.888 --> 00:03:44.424
Big. burly. bag. beard.
brunette. Five Bs.

78
00:03:44.559 --> 00:03:46.094
Do your job. go find him.

79
00:03:46.226 --> 00:03:47.795
When did you see
this individual?

80
00:03:47.929 --> 00:03:48.996
4:00 a.m. This morning.

81
00:03:49.130 --> 00:03:50.531
What were you doing up
at 4:00 a.m.?

82
00:03:50.665 --> 00:03:52.567
-4:00 a.m. club.
-What?

83
00:03:52.700 --> 00:03:55.636
Studies show that people
who get up at 4:00 a.m.
are more productive.

84
00:03:55.770 --> 00:03:58.573
maximize their day
and live five years longer
than the average person.

85
00:03:58.706 --> 00:03:59.874
You just made all that up.

86
00:04:00.007 --> 00:04:01.542
I'll send you some podcasts.

87
00:04:01.676 --> 00:04:04.512
Please don't.
And what do you do
every morning at 4:00 a.m.?

88
00:04:04.645 --> 00:04:06.714
Morning meditation.
followed by a red-light mask.

89
00:04:06.848 --> 00:04:10.885
followed by some journaling.
Peloton ride. cold plunge.
eastern sun exposure.

90
00:04:11.018 --> 00:04:12.720
I've never felt better.

91
00:04:12.854 --> 00:04:15.656
So. when did you see
Mr. Beardo Baggins over here?

92
00:04:15.790 --> 00:04:18.291
Yeah. so I went out
to get my meal plan.
that's when I saw the guy.

93
00:04:18.425 --> 00:04:20.427
He was
right next to Joelle's house.

94
00:04:23.598 --> 00:04:24.866
Joelle's.

95
00:04:26.134 --> 00:04:32.039
Yeah. Joelle and Eli's house.
Eli and Joelle's house.
Eli's house.

96
00:04:36.811 --> 00:04:37.845
[chuckles]

97
00:04:38.445 --> 00:04:40.748
-She was a beautiful woman.
-Was she?

98
00:04:40.882 --> 00:04:43.283
Paul. were you
and Joelle Hornbaker intimate?

99
00:04:44.585 --> 00:04:45.820
Oh. God. Eli!

100
00:04:45.953 --> 00:04:47.487
-Hey. Hey. hey.
-You killed her.
you son of a...

101
00:04:47.622 --> 00:04:49.356
-Eli! Eli!
-[shouts]

102
00:04:49.489 --> 00:04:52.325
He was sleeping with Joelle.
She tried to break it off.
and he killed her.

103
00:04:52.459 --> 00:04:54.128
Whoa. whoa. whoa.
I broke it off with her.

104
00:04:54.262 --> 00:04:55.663
[Will] Hey!

105
00:04:55.797 --> 00:04:57.532
Hey. listen.
I am sorry for your loss.

106
00:04:57.665 --> 00:04:59.466
but I'm gonna need you
to calm down

107
00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:00.868
before I have to put you
under arrest.

108
00:05:01.002 --> 00:05:02.804
-[Will] Get him out of here.
-Let's go.

109
00:05:03.470 --> 00:05:04.505
[Will] Okay.

110
00:05:06.073 --> 00:05:08.176
The truth. Right now.

111
00:05:08.776 --> 00:05:10.645
-I didn't kill her.
-But you had an affair.

112
00:05:10.778 --> 00:05:12.146
Well. okay. look. I was...

113
00:05:12.613 --> 00:05:15.415
I was over there for a dinner
party like last year. okay?

114
00:05:15.550 --> 00:05:17.218
We're at the table.
I'm across from her.

115
00:05:17.384 --> 00:05:19.386
All of a sudden.
I feel her foot on my crotch.

116
00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:22.089
-Oh. Paul--
-No. no.
it's not as sexy as it sounds.

117
00:05:22.223 --> 00:05:24.559
She was drunk.
I mean. she was. like.
really digging around in there

118
00:05:24.692 --> 00:05:27.528
-like she was trying
to find her keys.
-Paul. this is serious!

119
00:05:27.662 --> 00:05:30.698
Yeah. I know it's serious!
She was brutally murdered!

120
00:05:32.600 --> 00:05:35.970
We'd hook up
when Eli was away for business.
It was very casual--

121
00:05:36.103 --> 00:05:38.306
When's the last time
you two saw each other?

122
00:05:39.106 --> 00:05:40.473
Last night.

123
00:05:40.608 --> 00:05:43.010
Last night.
You mean before she was killed?

124
00:05:43.611 --> 00:05:47.380
I only went over there
to break things off with her.
which I did.

125
00:05:48.481 --> 00:05:50.985
-Then we had breakup sex.
-Oh. great.

126
00:05:51.118 --> 00:05:54.689
So. you're telling me
we're gonna find your DNA
inside the victim?

127
00:05:54.822 --> 00:05:56.691
-Hmm?
-[stammers]

128
00:05:56.824 --> 00:05:58.593
-Probably. yeah.
-Then you ran up
to the crime scene

129
00:05:58.726 --> 00:06:01.494
claiming you saw a shadowy.
bearded. faceless man.

130
00:06:01.629 --> 00:06:02.930
You know
what you sound like to me?

131
00:06:03.664 --> 00:06:05.833
-The murderer.
-The murderer.

132
00:06:07.335 --> 00:06:08.803
I don't think
he's the murderer.

133
00:06:08.936 --> 00:06:11.371
I think
he's a stupid. stupid man.
but he's not our guy.

134
00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:15.109
Well. he's the last known
person to see her alive.

135
00:06:15.243 --> 00:06:17.011
And we'll get DNA.

136
00:06:17.144 --> 00:06:18.346
[sighs]

137
00:06:18.478 --> 00:06:20.848
There's something different
about this case. Amanda.

138
00:06:20.982 --> 00:06:22.583
I don't have it all
figured out yet.

139
00:06:22.717 --> 00:06:25.485
but this was not
a crime of passion.

140
00:06:26.554 --> 00:06:30.091
Killer is patient. cold.
detail-oriented.

141
00:06:30.224 --> 00:06:31.926
none of which
reads like Paul Campano.

142
00:06:32.059 --> 00:06:33.160
Will might be right.

143
00:06:33.294 --> 00:06:35.830
Eli Hornbaker insisted
the nail gun wasn't his.

144
00:06:35.963 --> 00:06:38.766
so I traced the serial number
to a Brent Shipley.

145
00:06:38.900 --> 00:06:41.569
-Did you reach out?
-I don't think he'd answer.

146
00:06:41.702 --> 00:06:45.472
Brent Shipley was killed
last year in a home invasion.

147
00:06:46.274 --> 00:06:49.476
Same MO too. No fingerprints
and a weapon
left at the crime scene.

148
00:06:51.045 --> 00:06:52.380
You both know what that means.

149
00:06:54.447 --> 00:06:55.950
Serial killer.

150
00:07:00.755 --> 00:07:01.989
[Angie] What's it look like?

151
00:07:02.556 --> 00:07:04.158
Hit-and-run. No witnesses.

152
00:07:04.292 --> 00:07:07.962
A bagel? Are you kidding me?
Softball season
right around the corner.

153
00:07:08.495 --> 00:07:09.664
Kinda feels like
you don't care.

154
00:07:10.731 --> 00:07:12.099
[Angie] Mmm. Everything.

155
00:07:14.368 --> 00:07:17.004
Who thinks
this is a hit-and-run?
The car's still here. O'Hara.

156
00:07:17.138 --> 00:07:20.107
Yeah. well. he hit the guy
and then ran on foot.

157
00:07:20.574 --> 00:07:23.644
The car's registered
to a Benjamin Price.

158
00:07:24.145 --> 00:07:25.478
Well. it should be
easy to solve.

159
00:07:31.619 --> 00:07:34.221
You just had to get pregnant
during softball season.
huh. Polaski?

160
00:07:34.755 --> 00:07:36.557
Dude. the pregnancy
was unplanned.

161
00:07:36.691 --> 00:07:40.328
Yeah. except no one on our team
rounds the bases like you do.
Irreplaceable.

162
00:07:40.460 --> 00:07:41.796
Hey. what color's
the vic's hair?

163
00:07:41.929 --> 00:07:43.597
[sighs] Black.

164
00:07:43.731 --> 00:07:46.133
[Franklin]
Well. I got some white hair
here and some blood too.

165
00:07:46.267 --> 00:07:50.438
Yeah. his eyes
are swollen shut.
Whole face is swollen.

166
00:07:51.038 --> 00:07:52.940
He's red. but it doesn't
look like road rash.

167
00:07:53.074 --> 00:07:54.775
Can't even tell
where this guy got hit.

168
00:07:54.909 --> 00:07:57.445
You know. Heidi Klum was in
Victoria's Secret's runway show

169
00:07:57.578 --> 00:07:59.213
five weeks
after she gave birth.

170
00:07:59.347 --> 00:08:02.183
Ooh. You just walked
into a propeller. bud.

171
00:08:03.284 --> 00:08:05.953
Don't you ever compare me
to Heidi Klum again.

172
00:08:06.486 --> 00:08:08.488
or any other woman
who snapped back in five weeks.

173
00:08:09.256 --> 00:08:11.125
-I have a gun.
-Understood.

174
00:08:11.258 --> 00:08:12.526
-Okay.
-[Franklin] Got it.

175
00:08:13.294 --> 00:08:14.762
[Michael]
Take a look at his neck.

176
00:08:16.263 --> 00:08:18.799
[Angie] Yeah.
Broken trachea. at least.

177
00:08:18.933 --> 00:08:21.268
Still doesn't explain
the puffy eyes.

178
00:08:21.402 --> 00:08:24.538
[sniffs] Oh. Pepper spray.

179
00:08:24.672 --> 00:08:26.107
[Angie] Okay. so...

180
00:08:27.541 --> 00:08:31.479
dude gets hit
with pepper spray.
has an allergic reaction.

181
00:08:32.246 --> 00:08:36.917
stumbles out into the street
and gets hit by a car
on the throat.

182
00:08:37.051 --> 00:08:38.686
That's not real.

183
00:08:38.819 --> 00:08:42.189
You're right.
Because this is the driver.
His name is Ben Price.

184
00:08:42.323 --> 00:08:45.526
He's 35 years old
and not an organ donor.

185
00:08:45.659 --> 00:08:47.828
Our victim was the driver?
Who did he hit?

186
00:08:47.962 --> 00:08:49.697
And where are they?
And why is he dead?

187
00:08:49.830 --> 00:08:52.500
Well. he got a couple of texts
from somebody named Luna.

188
00:08:52.633 --> 00:08:53.868
"What did you hit?

189
00:08:54.001 --> 00:08:56.704
Are you okay? I can't believe
you hung up on me."

190
00:08:56.837 --> 00:08:58.672
-Let's find Luna.
-[Franklin] Let's find Luna.

191
00:09:01.008 --> 00:09:03.177
-[Angie] You don't want that.
do you?
-What?

192
00:09:07.248 --> 00:09:09.250
[Sandra] That's definitely
Daddy's nail gun.

193
00:09:09.817 --> 00:09:12.186
He always joked it was
the first Father's Day gift

194
00:09:12.319 --> 00:09:14.055
he didn't have to wear
on his feet.

195
00:09:15.656 --> 00:09:19.026
Have you ever seen
these people before. Sandra?

196
00:09:21.095 --> 00:09:22.396
I can't say that I have.

197
00:09:24.065 --> 00:09:25.733
What about the day
your dad was murdered?

198
00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:29.737
I know it's painful.
but is there anything
that you can share?

199
00:09:30.271 --> 00:09:32.106
My story hasn't changed.

200
00:09:32.239 --> 00:09:33.674
I stopped by to visit Daddy.

201
00:09:33.808 --> 00:09:37.411
and I found him laid out
in the living room. dead.

202
00:09:37.546 --> 00:09:39.580
His head was busted open
with a bat.

203
00:09:39.713 --> 00:09:42.750
[sniffles] The irony is
he hated baseball. [chuckles]

204
00:09:42.883 --> 00:09:46.587
-He didn't own the bat?
-Uh. I never saw it before
in my life.

205
00:09:50.691 --> 00:09:52.293
You know. I-I came here today

206
00:09:52.426 --> 00:09:54.762
hoping there was
some new information
about Daddy's killer.

207
00:09:54.895 --> 00:09:57.398
but it looks like I'm back here
playing storyteller
for y'all again.

208
00:09:57.532 --> 00:10:00.000
-I know that it's--
-You don't know a damn thing!

209
00:10:01.469 --> 00:10:02.603
Nothing.

210
00:10:04.171 --> 00:10:08.776
You're right. You're right.
I do not know anything
about your pain or your loss.

211
00:10:09.610 --> 00:10:12.046
But I do believe that
this murder is connected
to another murder.

212
00:10:12.179 --> 00:10:14.815
which means that we have
more information
than we did before.

213
00:10:14.949 --> 00:10:16.684
We're gonna catch him.

214
00:10:22.256 --> 00:10:26.660
I don't know how anyone
was able to sneak up on my dad.

215
00:10:27.228 --> 00:10:29.830
He was so cautious.
and he always had
his panic button.

216
00:10:30.532 --> 00:10:32.666
He wore that thing around
like a necklace.

217
00:10:34.935 --> 00:10:36.470
I always thought that maybe...

218
00:10:37.138 --> 00:10:38.607
Maybe your dad knew the killer.

219
00:10:39.106 --> 00:10:40.141
Yeah.

220
00:10:41.342 --> 00:10:42.376
[sighs]

221
00:10:53.921 --> 00:10:58.292
Joelle Hornbaker was killed
with a nail gun that belonged
to Brent Shipley.

222
00:10:59.594 --> 00:11:02.897
Brent Shipley was murdered
with a bat that wasn't his own.

223
00:11:03.430 --> 00:11:06.333
Maybe it belonged
to a previous victim
we don't know about yet.

224
00:11:08.669 --> 00:11:09.937
Maybe it's a pattern.

225
00:11:15.442 --> 00:11:17.478
[♪ sinister music playing]

226
00:11:23.518 --> 00:11:25.986
[breathing shakily]

227
00:11:30.424 --> 00:11:32.661
[muffled chattering]

228
00:11:51.646 --> 00:11:53.480
[on TV] <i>He's been dead</i>
<i>for almost a year now.</i>

229
00:11:53.615 --> 00:11:56.585
<i>Still you might have</i>
<i>some consideration</i>
<i>for your husband's memory.</i>

230
00:11:56.717 --> 00:11:59.220
<i>I don't see what</i>
<i>Edwin's got to do with this.</i>

231
00:11:59.987 --> 00:12:02.557
<i>I'm not leaving him.</i>
<i>I'm leaving you.</i>

232
00:12:04.191 --> 00:12:06.860
<i>After all we've tried</i>
<i>to do for you...</i>

233
00:12:09.296 --> 00:12:12.766
<i>You've both been so very kind</i>
<i>to me. but I'm not really...</i>

234
00:12:12.900 --> 00:12:16.403
So he takes something
from each victim and
murders the next guy with it.

235
00:12:16.538 --> 00:12:17.838
Mmm. It's cute.

236
00:12:17.972 --> 00:12:20.575
Little gimmicky. but whatever.
It's not a competition.

237
00:12:20.709 --> 00:12:24.044
Will. Will. Will. Will.
Will. Will. I must say.

238
00:12:24.679 --> 00:12:27.448
you needing me
to be the dark you...

239
00:12:29.450 --> 00:12:32.419
is truly flattering.
You must miss me.

240
00:12:33.387 --> 00:12:34.922
How's hell treating you. James?

241
00:12:35.055 --> 00:12:37.157
Hmm. Too many group activities.
Not a fan.

242
00:12:37.626 --> 00:12:39.093
You're going deep
with these "Will-o-visions."

243
00:12:39.226 --> 00:12:40.928
adding role-play. I like it.

244
00:12:42.263 --> 00:12:44.098
Trying to get inside
the killer's head.

245
00:12:44.633 --> 00:12:50.371
Sure. Whatever you need
to tell yourself.
Go ahead. Batter up.

246
00:12:53.874 --> 00:12:55.075
-[grunts]
-[bones crack]

247
00:12:59.046 --> 00:13:01.782
Oh. nice work.
What did we learn?

248
00:13:02.816 --> 00:13:04.251
The killer enjoyed it.

249
00:13:04.385 --> 00:13:08.022
Yeah. you did. I love seeing
this side of you. by the way.

250
00:13:08.155 --> 00:13:11.660
Imagine if I were alive.
we could rent a van
with no windows.

251
00:13:11.792 --> 00:13:13.628
Mmm. We'd have so much fun.

252
00:13:30.311 --> 00:13:31.445
Can I do this one?

253
00:13:32.146 --> 00:13:33.715
No.

254
00:13:33.847 --> 00:13:35.784
Look.
she's got a lot of energy.
You might need an extra hand.

255
00:13:40.689 --> 00:13:43.525
[gasps] No. please.
[whimpering. sobbing]

256
00:13:50.665 --> 00:13:51.700
Why did you stop?

257
00:13:52.232 --> 00:13:54.301
Someone must have
blocked her path.

258
00:13:54.803 --> 00:13:57.971
[both] But if someone blocked
poor Joelle from escaping.

259
00:13:58.105 --> 00:13:59.473
that must mean...

260
00:14:00.307 --> 00:14:02.142
There's two killers.

261
00:14:02.276 --> 00:14:05.346
Oh. It's such a joy
to watch you work again.

262
00:14:09.983 --> 00:14:12.687
So. Luna.
can you tell us anything
about what was happening

263
00:14:12.821 --> 00:14:14.955
leading up to Benjamin's death?

264
00:14:15.489 --> 00:14:16.791
You know. Ben was my man.

265
00:14:17.692 --> 00:14:20.227
My man. my man. my man.

266
00:14:21.261 --> 00:14:22.697
-I'll show you later.
-Okay.

267
00:14:23.330 --> 00:14:26.568
Uh. were you talking to Ben
right before he died?

268
00:14:26.701 --> 00:14:31.238
We had lunch at R. Thomas Grill
and were FaceTiming
after we left.

269
00:14:31.706 --> 00:14:33.374
We always FaceTimed
on the way home.

270
00:14:33.508 --> 00:14:34.908
While you were driving?

271
00:14:35.042 --> 00:14:37.679
We do it all the time.
Don't you?

272
00:14:37.812 --> 00:14:42.584
Well. no. 'cause it's illegal.
And you could get
in a car accident.

273
00:14:42.717 --> 00:14:44.184
Oh. well. that's not why he...

274
00:14:45.219 --> 00:14:47.154
I mean. maybe?

275
00:14:48.222 --> 00:14:51.892
Ben definitely hit something
because it cracked
his windshield.

276
00:14:52.025 --> 00:14:54.995
And I heard some lady yell.
"You killed my baby."

277
00:14:55.630 --> 00:14:56.897
"You killed my baby"?

278
00:14:57.030 --> 00:14:58.767
I could tell Ben was shook.

279
00:14:59.233 --> 00:15:02.269
He didn't want me
to see him like that.
so he said he'd call me back.

280
00:15:02.403 --> 00:15:04.037
[♪ intriguing music playing]

281
00:15:04.171 --> 00:15:05.439
But then he never did.

282
00:15:07.040 --> 00:15:09.176
What baby did Ben kill?

283
00:15:10.879 --> 00:15:14.749
Yeah. hi. I-I was calling
to see if you've had
any hit-and-run victims

284
00:15:14.883 --> 00:15:18.419
admitted today. or any sort of
vehicle-type-related injuries.

285
00:15:18.553 --> 00:15:19.854
Sure. I'll hold.

286
00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:22.489
Hey. what about Keaton?
He looks like
he's been hitting the gym.

287
00:15:23.090 --> 00:15:26.193
Oh. no. Keaton's still banned
for dropping that easy third
out last season.

288
00:15:27.261 --> 00:15:28.797
See? That's what
we're talking about.

289
00:15:28.929 --> 00:15:30.565
Can't you just
get a C-section now?

290
00:15:30.698 --> 00:15:32.734
-Just once.
-Thank you for checking. Okay.

291
00:15:32.867 --> 00:15:35.402
That's such a good idea.
I'm gonna do that.

292
00:15:36.203 --> 00:15:39.874
I'm gonna get a C-section so we
can win the interdepartmental
softball game.

293
00:15:40.575 --> 00:15:42.976
-Okay. is that sarcasm
or contempt?
-Contempt.

294
00:15:43.110 --> 00:15:45.345
Hey. All right. listen up.
email from Pete.

295
00:15:45.479 --> 00:15:47.916
"Tissue samples
came back from the lab."

296
00:15:48.048 --> 00:15:50.618
"The hair and blood
came from a skunk."

297
00:15:50.752 --> 00:15:53.353
A skunk? Crime scene
didn't smell like skunk at all.

298
00:15:53.487 --> 00:15:56.423
Could be a pet skunk.
Their owners remove
their anal glands.

299
00:15:56.957 --> 00:15:59.594
-How do you know that?
-And who would keep
a pet skunk?

300
00:15:59.727 --> 00:16:02.730
I think the more important
question is who would
kill someone over a pet skunk?

301
00:16:02.864 --> 00:16:08.770
Oh. Maybe this lady.
Daphne Bell.
She goes by Skunk Mother.

302
00:16:08.903 --> 00:16:10.572
She rehabilitates
injured skunks

303
00:16:10.705 --> 00:16:12.306
and has over 40
on her property.

304
00:16:12.439 --> 00:16:15.442
and it's less than a mile away
from the crime scene.

305
00:16:15.976 --> 00:16:17.545
Let's bring in
the Skunk Mother.

306
00:16:17.679 --> 00:16:19.413
Let's do it.

307
00:16:20.314 --> 00:16:24.619
Serial killer team-ups
are typically couples.
siblings. close friends.

308
00:16:25.520 --> 00:16:27.755
My guess is these two have
known each other a long time.

309
00:16:27.889 --> 00:16:31.860
Both felt ignored.
disrespected.
decided to take vengeance.

310
00:16:32.326 --> 00:16:33.595
Textbook injustice collectors.

311
00:16:33.728 --> 00:16:39.032
Exactly. It's a power trip.
Control the environment.

312
00:16:39.601 --> 00:16:44.706
Toy with the victims.
Leave your smarty-pants
murder weapon trophies

313
00:16:44.839 --> 00:16:47.207
and walk away feeling like
masters of the universe.

314
00:16:47.341 --> 00:16:49.511
I think that
Brent Shipley was killed
by someone he knew.

315
00:16:49.644 --> 00:16:51.478
We make a list
of all of his known associates.

316
00:16:51.613 --> 00:16:53.882
maybe one of them will
cross-reference with Hornbaker.

317
00:16:54.014 --> 00:16:57.317
I don't know.
Something tells me
these targets weren't personal.

318
00:16:58.452 --> 00:17:02.757
Victims could be anyone.
It's the act themselves
that are the point.

319
00:17:02.891 --> 00:17:04.324
Okay.
then what's the through line?

320
00:17:06.159 --> 00:17:11.031
Maybe it's access.
One of the killers
is the mastermind alpha.

321
00:17:11.733 --> 00:17:13.500
Other offers
something of value.

322
00:17:13.635 --> 00:17:14.936
A way to find victims.

323
00:17:16.203 --> 00:17:19.072
Your stupid friend Paul
is blowing up your case.

324
00:17:20.440 --> 00:17:23.477
<i>Hi. I'm Paul Campano</i>
<i>from Campano Motors.</i>

325
00:17:23.611 --> 00:17:26.179
<i>And I'm asking you</i>
<i>to help me find a murderer.</i>

326
00:17:26.313 --> 00:17:27.515
-[sighs]
<i>-He was last seen</i>

327
00:17:27.649 --> 00:17:29.116
<i>on Southwest Magnolia Avenue</i>

328
00:17:29.249 --> 00:17:32.020
<i>in Alpharetta at 4:00 a.m.</i>
<i>on Wednesday morning.</i>

329
00:17:32.152 --> 00:17:36.223
<i>Anyone with</i>
<i>credible information</i>
<i>leading to his capture</i>

330
00:17:36.356 --> 00:17:38.860
<i>will receive 15% off</i>
<i>at Campano Motors.</i>

331
00:17:38.993 --> 00:17:42.429
-[scoffs]
<i>-Please use</i>
<i>my Call Paul hotline.</i>

332
00:17:44.599 --> 00:17:45.700
Thanks. Paul.

333
00:17:56.176 --> 00:17:57.579
Paul. what are you doing?

334
00:17:57.712 --> 00:17:59.246
Hanging up my wanted posters.
You wanna help?

335
00:17:59.379 --> 00:18:02.149
You are really God's perfect.
stupid little creature.

336
00:18:02.282 --> 00:18:04.351
Eli's telling everybody
that I killed Joelle.

337
00:18:04.484 --> 00:18:06.888
I've worked too hard
to bounce back after
what happened to my family.

338
00:18:07.021 --> 00:18:08.188
I can't start over again.

339
00:18:08.322 --> 00:18:10.525
Would you stop?
If this is really the killer.

340
00:18:10.658 --> 00:18:12.492
the first thing he's gonna do
is shave off his beard.

341
00:18:12.627 --> 00:18:14.428
And also. you're telling
the killer who you are.

342
00:18:14.562 --> 00:18:16.631
where you work.
and that you can ID them.

343
00:18:16.764 --> 00:18:19.534
-Killers don't watch TikTok.
Trent.
-[engine revving]

344
00:18:19.667 --> 00:18:20.735
-Get down!
-Get down!

345
00:18:29.644 --> 00:18:30.979
Were you hit?

346
00:18:31.111 --> 00:18:34.281
[grunts] Ah. No.
I'm good. I'm good.

347
00:18:39.453 --> 00:18:42.189
-[radio chatter]
-[camera clicking]

348
00:18:46.293 --> 00:18:47.962
-You okay?
-No.

349
00:18:48.630 --> 00:18:50.999
My sex buddy's dead.
and I just got shot at.

350
00:18:51.131 --> 00:18:52.834
Yeah. well. you're still alive.

351
00:18:52.967 --> 00:18:55.302
Hey. you find
that third bullet?

352
00:18:55.435 --> 00:18:59.373
I'm still looking. but I boxed
and tagged two. 9mm for sure.

353
00:19:00.440 --> 00:19:01.809
Well. look at the bright side.
Paul.

354
00:19:01.943 --> 00:19:03.645
At least now we know
you're not a suspect.

355
00:19:04.512 --> 00:19:05.479
That's true.

356
00:19:05.613 --> 00:19:07.815
Except now I'm a marked man.

357
00:19:07.949 --> 00:19:09.449
Marked for death.

358
00:19:09.584 --> 00:19:11.318
There's no safe place for me.

359
00:19:12.386 --> 00:19:13.988
I bet there's somewhere
you can go.

360
00:19:17.157 --> 00:19:19.359
[♪ "Very Best Thing" playing]

361
00:19:20.094 --> 00:19:22.764
Do you know
what sleeping on a couch
will do to my spinal alignment?

362
00:19:22.897 --> 00:19:26.834
Oh. please.
Your track record with women.
this can't be your first couch.

363
00:19:28.268 --> 00:19:29.837
-Hey.
-All right. come on.
Dinner's ready.

364
00:19:29.971 --> 00:19:31.271
-[Betty whines]
-[knocks on door]

365
00:19:31.839 --> 00:19:33.041
Can you get that?

366
00:19:33.173 --> 00:19:35.342
Me? [stammers] What if
it's one of the killers?

367
00:19:35.475 --> 00:19:38.713
APD is curbside all night
watching our backs. We're fine.

368
00:19:42.684 --> 00:19:43.818
Oh. my God. you whore.

369
00:19:43.951 --> 00:19:45.653
So... [chuckling]
I hear you're still an idiot.

370
00:19:45.787 --> 00:19:48.856
You guys are having a baby?
This is crazy.

371
00:19:48.990 --> 00:19:50.525
I mean. I did call it
when we were kids.

372
00:19:50.658 --> 00:19:51.759
PeePee Percy
owes me two dollars.

373
00:19:51.893 --> 00:19:53.260
-Paul.
-So. when's the shower?

374
00:19:53.393 --> 00:19:55.063
-I can get you
a top-of-the-line car seat...
-Paul.

375
00:19:55.195 --> 00:19:56.229
...easy installation.
cup holders.

376
00:19:56.363 --> 00:19:57.364
My dealership
gets a great discou--

377
00:19:57.497 --> 00:19:58.700
It's not my baby.

378
00:19:59.366 --> 00:20:01.301
Okay? Angie's married.
Not to me.

379
00:20:02.003 --> 00:20:03.538
He's a doctor. Very charming.

380
00:20:03.671 --> 00:20:06.373
He likes worms. His wife died.
He didn't do it. It was cancer.

381
00:20:08.176 --> 00:20:10.745
-I wish I found
a better way to say this.
-Very accurate.

382
00:20:13.514 --> 00:20:15.016
[Will] What are you
doing here. Ang?

383
00:20:15.149 --> 00:20:16.551
I heard about
today's little shoot-out.

384
00:20:16.684 --> 00:20:18.553
so. uh.
I came to hear all about it.

385
00:20:18.686 --> 00:20:23.057
How is it that every time
the two of you get together.
something crazy happens?

386
00:20:23.191 --> 00:20:25.325
To be fair.
something crazy happens first.

387
00:20:25.459 --> 00:20:27.161
which then typically
brings us together.

388
00:20:27.294 --> 00:20:28.996
-Chicken and the egg.
-[Angie chuckles]

389
00:20:29.130 --> 00:20:30.497
This looks great.

390
00:20:30.631 --> 00:20:31.866
[chuckles]

391
00:20:32.567 --> 00:20:35.203
Boy. I'd love to see the look
on Mrs. Flannery's face

392
00:20:35.335 --> 00:20:37.105
if she saw the three of us
sitting here.

393
00:20:37.237 --> 00:20:39.774
Yeah. She'd pass out
from shock. that's for sure.

394
00:20:40.373 --> 00:20:43.443
So. uh.
do we all have our hankies?

395
00:20:43.578 --> 00:20:44.846
-Oh.
-Please.

396
00:20:44.979 --> 00:20:46.514
-I don't leave home without it.
-Always.

397
00:20:46.647 --> 00:20:48.616
<i>-Salud.</i>
-[Paul. Angie chuckling]

398
00:20:50.350 --> 00:20:52.053
"Dab. don't rub. Like a lady."

399
00:20:52.186 --> 00:20:53.955
We made her life
so much harder.

400
00:20:54.088 --> 00:20:56.691
Especially this guy.
Tormenting me every day.

401
00:20:56.824 --> 00:20:59.093
Oh. wait a minute. Trash.
You started it first.

402
00:20:59.227 --> 00:21:01.763
What? What is this.
revisionist theater?

403
00:21:01.896 --> 00:21:03.965
I clearly recall you
beating me up on the regular.

404
00:21:04.098 --> 00:21:05.800
Yeah. 'Cause you had it coming!

405
00:21:05.933 --> 00:21:08.770
-I had it coming?
How'd I have it coming--
-How's the case going?

406
00:21:08.903 --> 00:21:10.004
We're close.

407
00:21:10.838 --> 00:21:12.707
As soon as I figure out
what's connecting the victims.

408
00:21:12.840 --> 00:21:13.875
things will start
going our way.

409
00:21:14.008 --> 00:21:15.543
-So. Ang...
-Mmm?

410
00:21:15.676 --> 00:21:17.044
Are we planning
on breastfeeding?

411
00:21:17.612 --> 00:21:19.247
I'm sorry.
that's your business how?

412
00:21:19.379 --> 00:21:21.481
Better for the baby.
I'll send you some podcasts.

413
00:21:21.616 --> 00:21:22.917
-Please don't.
-Oh. studies show that

414
00:21:23.050 --> 00:21:24.351
it benefits the mother
just as much.

415
00:21:24.484 --> 00:21:25.553
I'm sure it does.

416
00:21:25.686 --> 00:21:27.320
Especially.
you'll bounce back quicker.

417
00:21:27.454 --> 00:21:29.657
You'll lose that weight like...
[snaps fingers] ...that.

418
00:21:29.791 --> 00:21:32.660
I think his heart
is in the right place.

419
00:21:32.794 --> 00:21:34.294
-Let's just say
he's consistent.
-But...

420
00:21:34.427 --> 00:21:35.696
-Mm-hmm.
-Y-Yeah.

421
00:21:35.830 --> 00:21:37.598
-I'm right here. guys.
-It's really on brand. though.

422
00:21:39.667 --> 00:21:42.737
[♪ sinister music playing]

423
00:21:44.605 --> 00:21:46.339
-[Will] <i>The killer enjoyed it.</i>
-[nail gun fires]

424
00:21:53.346 --> 00:21:54.381
[sighs]

425
00:21:55.082 --> 00:21:57.018
[breathes deeply]

426
00:22:08.963 --> 00:22:09.997
[sighs]

427
00:22:11.799 --> 00:22:12.834
[gasps]

428
00:22:18.072 --> 00:22:20.908
[Eduardo] <i>Cobb County</i>
<i>Sheriff's Department calling.</i>

429
00:22:21.943 --> 00:22:24.512
<i>-Cobb County</i>
<i>Sheriff's Department calling.</i>
-[sighs]

430
00:22:26.614 --> 00:22:27.982
[Will] This is Trent.

431
00:22:29.617 --> 00:22:32.053
Could you just tell me
why this couldn't wait
till morning?

432
00:22:32.587 --> 00:22:34.689
A detective
from Cobb County called.

433
00:22:34.822 --> 00:22:37.424
There's another case
from two years ago
that might fit our pattern.

434
00:22:37.558 --> 00:22:39.093
And you could've stayed
at the house.

435
00:22:40.061 --> 00:22:41.329
You look like E.T.

436
00:22:41.796 --> 00:22:43.264
E.T. go home. Will.

437
00:22:46.534 --> 00:22:48.336
[Eduardo]
<i>Martin Hill was killed</i>

438
00:22:48.468 --> 00:22:50.571
<i>with steel hedge clippers</i>
<i>that belonged to him.</i>

439
00:22:51.272 --> 00:22:56.577
<i>An autographed</i>
<i>Deion Sanders baseball bat</i>
<i>was stolen from the property.</i>

440
00:22:56.711 --> 00:22:59.213
Killed by his own
hedge clippers.

441
00:23:01.148 --> 00:23:03.150
It was the first kill.

442
00:23:06.220 --> 00:23:08.689
What's the connection
between these people?

443
00:23:17.632 --> 00:23:19.901
Why would I choose to kill you?

444
00:23:22.603 --> 00:23:24.605
[♪ sinister music playing]

445
00:23:30.811 --> 00:23:32.113
[TV static crackling]

446
00:23:34.882 --> 00:23:36.884
[James] I knew
you couldn't stay away.

447
00:23:37.718 --> 00:23:39.287
Get a taste
of something you liked?

448
00:23:40.588 --> 00:23:41.622
I'm not here to kill.

449
00:23:41.756 --> 00:23:44.457
Mmm.
But you're so good at it. Look.

450
00:23:52.867 --> 00:23:54.467
[water sloshing]

451
00:23:58.906 --> 00:24:03.476
[James] Will. this is boring.
Do you not see
we have hedge clippers?

452
00:24:03.611 --> 00:24:05.079
It's really hard
to stab through bone.

453
00:24:05.212 --> 00:24:07.815
but once you do.
it's really satisfying.

454
00:24:08.382 --> 00:24:11.686
Not interested. Now. can you
please go burn for eternity?

455
00:24:19.860 --> 00:24:21.595
[groans. grunting]

456
00:24:25.833 --> 00:24:28.869
One magnesium a day.
keeps the back pain away.

457
00:24:38.646 --> 00:24:41.048
Will. you started this.
It wasn't me who made up

458
00:24:41.182 --> 00:24:43.284
-some imaginary you
for playtime.
-[huffs]

459
00:24:43.417 --> 00:24:45.519
-Why am I even here?
-Shut up.

460
00:24:45.653 --> 00:24:48.122
No. this is who you are.

461
00:24:48.255 --> 00:24:51.659
I'm not like you. okay?
I solve crimes.
I'm here for the victims.

462
00:24:51.792 --> 00:24:54.795
Oh. stop with your do-gooder
crap. You can't hide from me.

463
00:24:54.929 --> 00:24:57.565
You're here for the killers.
You like it.

464
00:24:57.698 --> 00:25:02.903
You wanna stab that guy.
Do it. Do it. Do it. Do it.
Do it. Do it. Do it. Do it.

465
00:25:03.037 --> 00:25:04.705
Do it. Do it.

466
00:25:04.839 --> 00:25:05.940
-Do it.
-[grunts]

467
00:25:06.073 --> 00:25:07.108
[grunts]

468
00:25:07.742 --> 00:25:09.677
[grunts]
So. is this what you want. huh?

469
00:25:09.810 --> 00:25:12.380
-Oh. now we're talking.
sonny boy.
-[grunts]

470
00:25:12.513 --> 00:25:14.648
-Is this what you want?
-I think it's what you want.

471
00:25:14.782 --> 00:25:16.083
-[grunts]
-[squelching]

472
00:25:18.019 --> 00:25:19.053
Yeah.

473
00:25:22.289 --> 00:25:23.724
This is what I want.

474
00:25:31.899 --> 00:25:33.401
No. [gasps]

475
00:25:33.534 --> 00:25:35.536
No. no. no.
that's not what I meant.

476
00:25:37.171 --> 00:25:38.539
I didn't mean to kill him.

477
00:25:39.607 --> 00:25:42.043
-[Paul] <i>Will.</i>
-I meant to kill you.

478
00:25:42.710 --> 00:25:44.412
-[Paul] Will.
-[gasps. panting]

479
00:25:44.545 --> 00:25:46.080
Hey. Whoa.

480
00:25:46.213 --> 00:25:48.449
-Will. Hey. Will. Hey. hey.
-[grunting]
I meant to kill you!

481
00:25:48.582 --> 00:25:51.318
Will! Will. it's Paul!
It's Paul. It's okay.

482
00:25:51.786 --> 00:25:53.421
[exhales. gasps]

483
00:25:53.587 --> 00:25:57.158
Hey. It's okay.
You're here. you're here.
We're at GBI.

484
00:25:58.025 --> 00:25:59.226
It's okay. Will.

485
00:25:59.727 --> 00:26:01.128
[whines]

486
00:26:01.262 --> 00:26:04.632
-It's too much.
-Okay. okay. wait. wait. wait.
Here.

487
00:26:04.765 --> 00:26:05.966
Good girl. I got you.

488
00:26:06.100 --> 00:26:07.068
[groans]

489
00:26:07.201 --> 00:26:08.569
-Here.
-[breathing heavily]

490
00:26:08.702 --> 00:26:09.904
Here's your dog.

491
00:26:10.671 --> 00:26:11.739
Okay.

492
00:26:12.473 --> 00:26:13.641
Okay. let's just. uh...

493
00:26:13.774 --> 00:26:17.311
-[breathes deeply]
-Let's breathe. Long exhale.

494
00:26:18.379 --> 00:26:20.881
-[Paul exhales]
-[breathing deeply]

495
00:26:21.015 --> 00:26:23.017
That's good. That's good.

496
00:26:23.651 --> 00:26:24.685
You're okay.

497
00:26:25.820 --> 00:26:27.054
You're all good. buddy.

498
00:26:28.189 --> 00:26:29.623
[sighs. chuckles]

499
00:26:29.757 --> 00:26:30.858
Man.

500
00:26:31.358 --> 00:26:33.494
Your job is tough.
Why do you put yourself
through this?

501
00:26:33.627 --> 00:26:34.662
[sighing]

502
00:26:34.795 --> 00:26:36.464
[♪ sinister music playing]

503
00:26:36.597 --> 00:26:38.199
Anuli Springs Water.

504
00:26:40.501 --> 00:26:41.735
What?

505
00:26:41.869 --> 00:26:43.604
Anuli Springs Water.

506
00:26:45.639 --> 00:26:46.941
That's their way in.

507
00:26:49.578 --> 00:26:51.745
That's how the killers
find their victims.

508
00:26:56.684 --> 00:27:01.222
I admit to everything.
It was me. I'm prepared
to face the consequences.

509
00:27:01.789 --> 00:27:04.325
All right.
let's start from the beginning.

510
00:27:04.925 --> 00:27:09.830
My skunk Pernie.
short for Copernicus.
escaped from the yard again.

511
00:27:09.964 --> 00:27:12.099
I chased him
down to the street.

512
00:27:12.233 --> 00:27:14.001
calling his name.
but he didn't stop.

513
00:27:14.135 --> 00:27:17.638
and I tried to get
the attention of the car
speeding down the road.

514
00:27:17.771 --> 00:27:19.541
and he didn't stop either.

515
00:27:19.673 --> 00:27:21.976
Uh. yeah. he didn't see you
because he was FaceTiming.

516
00:27:22.109 --> 00:27:24.478
Well. he hit Pernie.
He hit my baby.

517
00:27:24.613 --> 00:27:28.449
[shakily] And the man stopped
right away and got out.

518
00:27:28.583 --> 00:27:32.686
but by then I was just so angry
that I picked up a rock.

519
00:27:32.820 --> 00:27:34.889
and I threw it at his car

520
00:27:35.022 --> 00:27:38.459
and. uh. I think
it cracked the windshield.

521
00:27:38.593 --> 00:27:41.762
-I bet he didn't like that.
-No. he didn't.

522
00:27:41.896 --> 00:27:44.298
He charged like
he was gonna hit me.

523
00:27:44.431 --> 00:27:47.636
and I-I felt like
I was in danger...

524
00:27:47.768 --> 00:27:50.539
so I pepper sprayed him
right in the eyes.

525
00:27:50.671 --> 00:27:55.209
Wait. let me understand this.
Your skunks can't spray.
so you do?

526
00:27:55.342 --> 00:27:58.445
I'm their mother.
I spray. so they don't have to.

527
00:27:58.580 --> 00:27:59.980
Makes sense.

528
00:28:00.114 --> 00:28:02.683
So what happened
after you sprayed?

529
00:28:02.816 --> 00:28:04.818
[sighs] I scooped up Pernie

530
00:28:04.952 --> 00:28:07.888
and got
the H-E-double-hockey-sticks
out of there.

531
00:28:09.323 --> 00:28:11.560
-That's it?
-That's it.

532
00:28:11.692 --> 00:28:14.228
Daphne. you said you were ready
to admit to everything.

533
00:28:14.795 --> 00:28:15.996
I did.

534
00:28:16.797 --> 00:28:18.199
Isn't that why I'm here?

535
00:28:18.332 --> 00:28:20.868
I figured the man must have
pressed charges against me

536
00:28:21.001 --> 00:28:23.737
for damaging his car
and pepper spraying him.

537
00:28:24.905 --> 00:28:28.008
The man can't press charges
because he's dead.

538
00:28:28.142 --> 00:28:29.810
What?

539
00:28:29.944 --> 00:28:31.879
You didn't notice him having
an allergic reaction
to the pepper spray?

540
00:28:32.012 --> 00:28:35.617
No. I just ran.
He-He was alive when I left.

541
00:28:35.749 --> 00:28:40.421
[gasps] Am I going to jail?
Do prisons allow pets?

542
00:28:41.855 --> 00:28:44.358
Oh. I need my babies.

543
00:28:44.491 --> 00:28:46.193
[crying]

544
00:28:47.027 --> 00:28:48.495
She broke the windshield.

545
00:28:49.163 --> 00:28:50.599
So?

546
00:28:51.832 --> 00:28:53.133
So...

547
00:28:57.238 --> 00:28:58.439
Why can't I go with you?

548
00:28:59.907 --> 00:29:01.710
Because you are a civilian.

549
00:29:01.842 --> 00:29:03.944
I'm just getting records
of delivery schedules.

550
00:29:06.247 --> 00:29:07.982
-Here.
-[♪ "Run Like the River"
playing on radio]

551
00:29:08.115 --> 00:29:09.950
Sorry. I don't have
a bowl of water for you.

552
00:29:10.451 --> 00:29:12.419
That's-That's really insulting.

553
00:29:12.953 --> 00:29:16.423
Don't get out.
don't talk to anyone.
and don't touch anything.

554
00:29:16.558 --> 00:29:17.758
♪ <i>One hopeful road</i> ♪

555
00:29:17.891 --> 00:29:20.761
♪ <i>That my mamma showed to me</i> ♪

556
00:29:20.894 --> 00:29:22.096
[sighs]

557
00:29:22.229 --> 00:29:24.064
♪ <i>From the moment</i>
<i>I first standed</i> ♪

558
00:29:24.198 --> 00:29:27.167
♪ <i>I didn't know</i>
<i>Back there and then</i>
<i>She released me free</i> ♪

559
00:29:27.301 --> 00:29:29.069
♪ <i>From that patched-up</i>
<i>Shackle-down</i> ♪

560
00:29:43.817 --> 00:29:46.086
Special Agent Will Trent
at the GBI.

561
00:29:46.220 --> 00:29:48.822
Is there a manager around
I can talk to?

562
00:29:49.524 --> 00:29:50.625
Uh...

563
00:29:51.125 --> 00:29:54.028
Not a one. Special Agent Trent.
but what can I do for you?

564
00:29:58.132 --> 00:30:00.501
Special Agent Paul Campano.
[chuckles]

565
00:30:00.968 --> 00:30:02.269
Doesn't sound half bad.

566
00:30:02.403 --> 00:30:04.739
I need delivery route info
from the last two years

567
00:30:04.872 --> 00:30:08.208
along with corresponding
driver employee records.
Can you do that?

568
00:30:08.342 --> 00:30:10.811
Well. that-that is definitely
gonna be a request
for a manager. Uh...

569
00:30:10.944 --> 00:30:13.548
Let me see what I can dig up
on the computer.
You mind waiting here?

570
00:30:13.682 --> 00:30:14.948
-No problem.
-Cool.

571
00:30:21.288 --> 00:30:23.123
Hey. Mr. Anson.

572
00:30:24.592 --> 00:30:25.893
Your neck's bleeding.

573
00:30:28.495 --> 00:30:30.565
[chuckles] Thanks.

574
00:30:34.803 --> 00:30:36.937
[♪ ominous music playing]

575
00:30:37.071 --> 00:30:40.508
Eduardo. do an image search
for Blair Anson in Georgia.

576
00:30:40.642 --> 00:30:41.676
[Eduardo] <i>Searching.</i>

577
00:30:47.081 --> 00:30:48.616
[♪ tense music playing]

578
00:30:54.922 --> 00:30:57.091
The third bullet was found
near the Paul Campano shooting.

579
00:30:57.224 --> 00:30:58.859
Someone found it
in their mailbox.

580
00:30:58.992 --> 00:31:02.096
The bullet was a .38.
not the 9mm
reported in the summary.

581
00:31:02.229 --> 00:31:04.298
A crime scene specialist
would know the difference.

582
00:31:04.431 --> 00:31:07.401
You think a GBI crime scene
specialist falsified evidence?

583
00:31:07.535 --> 00:31:09.169
Travis Nash.
He was at the scene.

584
00:31:10.003 --> 00:31:12.072
Amanda. It's him.

585
00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:15.610
[♪ "Run Like the River"
continues on radio]

586
00:31:15.744 --> 00:31:17.044
Hmm.

587
00:31:17.177 --> 00:31:18.513
Yeah. there it is.

588
00:31:19.380 --> 00:31:20.849
Paul Campano.

589
00:31:22.517 --> 00:31:25.419
-How you doing?
-Hey. guy.
You were at the. uh...

590
00:31:25.553 --> 00:31:29.056
-the crime scene yesterday.
right?
-Yeah. [chuckles] Yeah.

591
00:31:29.189 --> 00:31:30.759
[♪ sinister music playing]

592
00:31:30.891 --> 00:31:32.926
Now. how about we go inside
and see your friend?

593
00:31:35.028 --> 00:31:38.165
-Hey. GBI. Get to the exit.
-Yes. sir.

594
00:32:01.321 --> 00:32:02.956
[gunfire]

595
00:32:06.393 --> 00:32:10.464
Blair Anson. I know about you
and your partner.

596
00:32:11.398 --> 00:32:13.467
You guys thought
you made a great team. huh?

597
00:32:13.601 --> 00:32:16.336
You knew how to get into homes.
he knew how to
clean up murders.

598
00:32:16.470 --> 00:32:18.573
Nobody can ignore you now.
right?

599
00:32:24.244 --> 00:32:26.980
Did you figure me out too.
Special Agent Trent?

600
00:32:27.114 --> 00:32:28.315
Paul. are you okay?

601
00:32:28.449 --> 00:32:30.117
Oh. sure. yeah.

602
00:32:30.250 --> 00:32:32.419
Besides having this gun
to my head.
everything's peaches and gravy.

603
00:32:32.887 --> 00:32:35.189
Oh. you don't know how long
I've been waiting for this.

604
00:32:39.861 --> 00:32:41.228
[grunting]

605
00:32:43.898 --> 00:32:45.600
[Travis] Get off!

606
00:32:48.469 --> 00:32:49.970
[grunting]

607
00:33:05.152 --> 00:33:06.688
Everyone thinks
you're such a hotshot.

608
00:33:06.821 --> 00:33:08.823
I do all the work.
You get all the credit.

609
00:33:08.957 --> 00:33:11.793
Make this easy on yourself.
Put down the knife.

610
00:33:14.662 --> 00:33:16.163
You're always giving orders.

611
00:33:16.296 --> 00:33:18.332
But you're not the one
in charge here.
Special Agent Trent.

612
00:33:18.465 --> 00:33:20.467
[grunting]

613
00:33:26.808 --> 00:33:28.041
So what?

614
00:33:28.943 --> 00:33:30.143
You feel overlooked?

615
00:33:30.645 --> 00:33:33.313
You think
that gives you a reason
to kill people in cold blood?

616
00:33:33.447 --> 00:33:34.481
Yeah.

617
00:33:35.517 --> 00:33:36.483
It does.

618
00:33:36.618 --> 00:33:38.218
[grunting]

619
00:34:02.309 --> 00:34:03.377
Do it. you freak.

620
00:34:06.346 --> 00:34:07.447
Do it!

621
00:34:07.582 --> 00:34:09.149
[groaning]

622
00:34:15.088 --> 00:34:16.323
Is it over?

623
00:34:18.760 --> 00:34:22.429
-Yeah. it's over.
-[sirens wailing]

624
00:34:25.667 --> 00:34:27.936
Thank you so much
for coming back in. Luna.
We just...

625
00:34:28.068 --> 00:34:30.304
We have one quick
follow-up question.

626
00:34:30.437 --> 00:34:34.676
You said you were on the phone
with Ben when he hit something

627
00:34:34.809 --> 00:34:37.011
-and that cracked
the windshield.
-Yeah.

628
00:34:37.144 --> 00:34:38.245
But that's not what happened.

629
00:34:38.378 --> 00:34:40.080
What? Yes. it is. [chuckles]

630
00:34:40.213 --> 00:34:42.584
We talked to
the. uh. Skunk Mother.

631
00:34:42.717 --> 00:34:44.351
The who?

632
00:34:44.484 --> 00:34:47.555
Your boyfriend hit a skunk
that belonged to a woman
called the Skunk Mother.

633
00:34:47.689 --> 00:34:49.824
She got mad.
threw a rock at the car

634
00:34:49.958 --> 00:34:51.458
right as he was
getting out of it.

635
00:34:51.593 --> 00:34:53.728
She threw a rock. So what?

636
00:34:53.861 --> 00:34:56.096
So how did you know
the windshield was cracked?

637
00:34:56.229 --> 00:34:59.333
You said Ben hung up the phone
before he got out of the car.

638
00:34:59.466 --> 00:35:02.102
She didn't throw the rock
and break the windshield

639
00:35:02.235 --> 00:35:03.605
until he was
getting out of the car.

640
00:35:03.738 --> 00:35:05.540
So how did you know about it?

641
00:35:06.273 --> 00:35:08.241
I figured that's what happened.

642
00:35:08.876 --> 00:35:12.046
Guess you figured so much
you drove yourself
to the crime scene. huh?

643
00:35:12.614 --> 00:35:14.582
What? What are you saying?

644
00:35:14.716 --> 00:35:16.651
You think I had something
to do with Ben dying?

645
00:35:16.784 --> 00:35:18.620
We pinged your phone
to the nearest tower

646
00:35:18.753 --> 00:35:20.822
and saw that
you were in the area
of the crime scene

647
00:35:20.955 --> 00:35:22.590
at the time of the murder.

648
00:35:22.724 --> 00:35:25.860
and witnesses
at R. Thomas Grill say
you threatened to kill him.

649
00:35:26.393 --> 00:35:28.195
Couples say crazy things
when they're mad.

650
00:35:28.328 --> 00:35:31.131
-[Franklin] Mm-hmm.
-Yeah. Here's what I think
happened.

651
00:35:31.599 --> 00:35:33.835
I think you followed him
while you were on the phone.

652
00:35:33.968 --> 00:35:37.505
and you pulled over
when you saw his car stopped
in the middle of the road.

653
00:35:37.639 --> 00:35:40.407
Imagine your surprise
to see Ben on the ground

654
00:35:40.541 --> 00:35:42.644
having an allergic reaction
to pepper spray.

655
00:35:42.777 --> 00:35:44.912
You could have saved him.

656
00:35:45.046 --> 00:35:48.916
Instead. you walked over there
and stomped on his throat.

657
00:35:49.050 --> 00:35:50.450
Was he cheating. Luna?

658
00:35:51.318 --> 00:35:53.387
Did your man.
your man. your man
wanna call things off?

659
00:35:53.521 --> 00:35:55.322
What made you so mad?

660
00:35:56.824 --> 00:36:00.128
[scoffs]
I supported that bastard
through the pandemic.

661
00:36:02.030 --> 00:36:04.364
He would've been on the street
if it weren't for me.

662
00:36:04.498 --> 00:36:06.100
He just starts making
a little bit of money.

663
00:36:06.233 --> 00:36:09.871
and then he wants to leave me
for a stripper
at Clermont Lounge.

664
00:36:10.638 --> 00:36:12.674
[scoffs] He got off easy.

665
00:36:20.148 --> 00:36:21.448
What's the matter
with you guys?

666
00:36:21.582 --> 00:36:24.719
We caught the killer.
We exonerated the Skunk Mother.

667
00:36:24.852 --> 00:36:26.120
All's right with the world.

668
00:36:26.253 --> 00:36:28.388
-We still need a shortstop.
Polaski.
-It's over.

669
00:36:28.523 --> 00:36:31.191
We looked everywhere.
There's nothing we can do.

670
00:36:31.324 --> 00:36:32.426
-[elevator bell dings]
-[sighs]

671
00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:34.662
Maybe we can settle
for a skunky mascot.

672
00:36:34.796 --> 00:36:37.031
Daphne. Hi.
What are you doing here?

673
00:36:37.165 --> 00:36:38.733
I'm dropping off
some thank-you cookies

674
00:36:38.866 --> 00:36:40.467
for not charging me
with murder.

675
00:36:40.601 --> 00:36:42.235
'Cause you didn't murder him.

676
00:36:42.369 --> 00:36:43.571
Take the win. Polaski.

677
00:36:43.705 --> 00:36:46.339
Oh. they're black and white.
of course. 'cause the...

678
00:36:46.974 --> 00:36:49.844
Oh. and you'll be happy to know
that Pernie is on the road
to recovery.

679
00:36:49.977 --> 00:36:52.080
Oh. good. This is Pernie here?

680
00:36:52.212 --> 00:36:53.881
Oh. no. this is Crusemire.

681
00:36:54.015 --> 00:36:55.282
-[Angie] Oh.
-Say hello. baby.

682
00:36:55.415 --> 00:36:56.584
-Hey. Crusemire.
-[Angie] Hi.

683
00:36:56.718 --> 00:36:57.685
-[chirrs]
-[all] Oh!

684
00:36:57.819 --> 00:36:59.386
-Uh-oh. Okay.
-Crusemire!

685
00:36:59.520 --> 00:37:01.055
-Oh. no. Okay.
-Oh. no.

686
00:37:01.189 --> 00:37:02.790
-See if he went that way.
all right?
-What is that?

687
00:37:02.924 --> 00:37:04.525
[Michael] It's okay.
He can't spray you.

688
00:37:04.659 --> 00:37:07.427
Actually. he hasn't had
his anal glands removed yet.

689
00:37:07.562 --> 00:37:10.230
You mean to tell me you brought
a loaded skunk into the APD?

690
00:37:10.363 --> 00:37:11.532
That's how people get hurt.

691
00:37:12.066 --> 00:37:13.101
[imitates skunk squealing]

692
00:37:13.233 --> 00:37:14.202
[Franklin] Shh!

693
00:37:14.334 --> 00:37:16.369
No sudden moves.
No loud noises.

694
00:37:16.504 --> 00:37:19.841
There is a skunk. it's loose.
and it has its anal glands.

695
00:37:19.974 --> 00:37:22.210
Crusemire.
[imitating skunk squealing]

696
00:37:23.376 --> 00:37:24.912
How do we know
if it's gonna spray?

697
00:37:25.046 --> 00:37:28.281
Oh. we're fine unless
he starts fluffing his tail.

698
00:37:28.415 --> 00:37:30.551
-[chirrs]
-And he's fluffing.

699
00:37:30.685 --> 00:37:32.053
[all gasping]

700
00:37:32.186 --> 00:37:33.921
[♪ amusing.
tense music playing]

701
00:37:39.694 --> 00:37:40.895
-Whoa.
-Whoa.

702
00:37:43.430 --> 00:37:44.766
Nice slide.

703
00:37:46.200 --> 00:37:47.235
What's your name?

704
00:37:47.835 --> 00:37:50.071
Officer Sam Atkins. sir.

705
00:37:50.204 --> 00:37:51.438
You fresh out of the academy.
Sam?

706
00:37:51.572 --> 00:37:52.573
First week here.

707
00:37:52.707 --> 00:37:54.407
Well. congratulations.

708
00:37:54.542 --> 00:37:57.812
You're the new shortstop
for the APD softball team.
You played ball before?

709
00:37:57.945 --> 00:37:59.614
I played for Atlanta Tech.

710
00:37:59.747 --> 00:38:03.416
I was actually recruited
to a Double-A team.
but I had a higher purpose.

711
00:38:03.951 --> 00:38:05.586
-Yes. you do.
-Yes. you do.

712
00:38:05.720 --> 00:38:09.322
Hey. team loves hazing rookies.
so this is on you to handle.
Sammy.

713
00:38:09.456 --> 00:38:10.490
Good luck.

714
00:38:21.368 --> 00:38:22.469
Hmm. Heading home?

715
00:38:22.970 --> 00:38:25.438
Yeah. early tee time
at the club.

716
00:38:25.573 --> 00:38:27.775
-I am back. baby. [chuckles]
-[chuckles]

717
00:38:28.509 --> 00:38:31.378
Hey. random thought.
you ever figure out how
those two guys knew each other?

718
00:38:31.512 --> 00:38:33.380
Friends since
elementary school.

719
00:38:33.915 --> 00:38:35.850
Tormented in arms. apparently.

720
00:38:35.983 --> 00:38:38.986
Well. I guess we shouldn't be
so hard on ourselves. huh?

721
00:38:39.120 --> 00:38:40.121
-[chuckles]
-Mmm.

722
00:38:40.621 --> 00:38:43.825
Betty. I'm not taking you home.
Get out of there.

723
00:38:43.958 --> 00:38:45.425
Why is your dog so hot for me?

724
00:38:45.560 --> 00:38:47.195
Oh. I don't know.

725
00:38:52.099 --> 00:38:53.768
Hey. Paul.

726
00:38:55.136 --> 00:38:56.469
What did you mean

727
00:38:57.638 --> 00:38:59.173
when you said I started it?

728
00:39:02.009 --> 00:39:04.011
You really don't remember.
do you?

729
00:39:08.149 --> 00:39:09.650
You beat me up first.

730
00:39:09.784 --> 00:39:11.752
What? No. I did not.

731
00:39:11.886 --> 00:39:13.621
Why would I make that up?

732
00:39:14.188 --> 00:39:16.791
When I first got to the home.
I was so scared.

733
00:39:16.924 --> 00:39:19.694
I-I didn't know anybody.
all the toys were broken.

734
00:39:19.827 --> 00:39:21.394
And you came back
right after me.

735
00:39:21.529 --> 00:39:24.464
Uh. you got kicked out
of a foster home
or something. right?

736
00:39:24.599 --> 00:39:26.466
[♪ ominous music playing]

737
00:39:26.601 --> 00:39:28.069
Sleeveless Jack.

738
00:39:28.202 --> 00:39:30.872
I will shoot everyone
in this house!

739
00:39:31.539 --> 00:39:32.874
[young Will] No!

740
00:39:33.007 --> 00:39:34.876
No! Jack! No!

741
00:39:35.009 --> 00:39:36.577
-[gunshot]
-[sobbing] I'm so sorry.

742
00:39:36.711 --> 00:39:37.678
[♪ pensive music playing]

743
00:39:37.812 --> 00:39:39.614
Well. I remember
picking up a toy gun

744
00:39:39.747 --> 00:39:42.583
and asking you if you wanted
to play cops and robbers.

745
00:39:43.184 --> 00:39:45.052
I pointed the gun at you.
and you just...

746
00:39:45.186 --> 00:39:48.556
I mean. for whatever reason.
you just snapped.

747
00:39:48.689 --> 00:39:50.324
I tackled you.

748
00:39:52.560 --> 00:39:53.694
I beat you up.

749
00:39:57.231 --> 00:39:58.266
[sighs]

750
00:39:59.333 --> 00:40:00.735
Why couldn't I remember?

751
00:40:00.868 --> 00:40:02.737
And you had this look
in your eye.

752
00:40:03.537 --> 00:40:04.772
I didn't even
remember that part

753
00:40:04.906 --> 00:40:06.507
until you came at me
this morning.

754
00:40:07.074 --> 00:40:08.109
It was the same look.

755
00:40:09.210 --> 00:40:12.980
Yeah. well.
you got me back for years.

756
00:40:13.114 --> 00:40:16.183
Yeah. well. the best defense
is a good offense.

757
00:40:16.317 --> 00:40:18.085
Couldn't let you
have the upper hand.

758
00:40:19.921 --> 00:40:22.690
A year ago. I'd flat out deny
this ever happened.

759
00:40:25.393 --> 00:40:26.426
[sighs]

760
00:40:27.494 --> 00:40:28.796
But now I can't.

761
00:40:31.532 --> 00:40:36.904
I'm trying so hard
to stay on the right path.

762
00:40:38.205 --> 00:40:40.174
[♪ emotional music playing]

763
00:40:40.308 --> 00:40:42.910
Not letting my past
control my future.

764
00:40:45.980 --> 00:40:48.282
You know.
maybe I'm just lying to myself.

765
00:40:48.950 --> 00:40:50.051
You're not lying.

766
00:40:50.885 --> 00:40:52.153
These killers...

767
00:40:53.187 --> 00:40:55.289
I don't know.
It's like I understood them.

768
00:40:57.425 --> 00:40:58.626
The fear.

769
00:40:59.694 --> 00:41:00.728
The rage.

770
00:41:03.097 --> 00:41:04.497
I feel those same things.

771
00:41:06.167 --> 00:41:10.671
Anybody who's been through what
we've been through
has a monster inside.

772
00:41:10.805 --> 00:41:12.306
[♪ "Looking Too Closely"
playing]

773
00:41:12.440 --> 00:41:17.144
But you've turned it
towards something good.

774
00:41:17.278 --> 00:41:19.246
That's why you're different.
You're better than them.

775
00:41:19.380 --> 00:41:20.581
It's the same.

776
00:41:21.782 --> 00:41:25.419
Power over people.
Control over a situation.

777
00:41:28.789 --> 00:41:31.625
I felt way too comfortable
inside their mind.

778
00:41:34.528 --> 00:41:36.230
I nearly killed Nash.

779
00:41:38.532 --> 00:41:40.301
I didn't have to. but. uh...

780
00:41:45.206 --> 00:41:46.507
I wanted to.

781
00:41:51.145 --> 00:41:54.315
-You can't let it win. Will.
You can't.
-[sighs]

782
00:41:55.483 --> 00:41:58.619
Every day.
I try to get out of my own way.

783
00:41:58.753 --> 00:42:01.555
so I can do
whatever it is I'm here to do.

784
00:42:01.689 --> 00:42:04.525
You know? And some days I win.
some days I lose.

785
00:42:05.659 --> 00:42:09.530
Some days I bang my neighbor.
and some days
I can't even get out of bed.

786
00:42:10.498 --> 00:42:11.899
but I keep fighting.

787
00:42:13.567 --> 00:42:15.202
You gotta keep fighting too.

788
00:42:22.710 --> 00:42:24.245
[sighs]

788
00:42:25.305 --> 00:43:25.393
